<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,508,756]" pageId="1" pageNumber="147">Only a brief generic diagnosis is given because the genus is monotypic and the description of the species follows below.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,508,756]" pageId="1" pageNumber="147">
Adult female oval, posterior end rounded without anal lobes. Antennae 
<number box="[960,971,605,628]" pageId="1" pageNumber="147" value="3.0">3</number>
-segmented; frontal lobes absent. Legs well developed but small for size of body, claw with a denticle. Anal ring small, situated ventrally at posterior end, with pores and 
<number box="[200,213,669,692]" pageId="1" pageNumber="147" value="6.0">6</number>
setae. Marginal setae mostly truncate-conical with tip bifid. Dorsal setae similar to marginal setae but much smaller, usually with tip bifid. Microtubular ducts present, each with bilocular orifice. Reticulated plate-like sclerotisations present on dorsum and along margins of venter. Quinquelocular pores present on venter only.
</paragraph>
